turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail added a second Scooby van to her motorcade, which is a GMC version of the original Chevy conversion van. Both vans are armored, nearly identical, and have New York license plates. The first van, nicknamed "Scooby" after the Scooby-Doo cartoon, has a mustard-yellow New York tag, while the second van has blue and white plates of a different design. The additional vehicle is believed to be a security measure to create confusion and discourage potential attackers. The Secret Service does not comment on security arrangements for dignitaries.

A Georgia mother of six, Kalimah Dixon, is left homeless and in need of assistance after a fire destroyed her rented condo, leaving her children without any possessions. Dixon, who was studying business management, had recently quit her job to focus on her education full-time. She is now struggling to find a new permanent home for her family as she is unemployed. The family is currently staying with a friend, far from their children's schools, and face challenges in finding shelter that can accommodate all of them. Dixon has started a GoFundMe page to raise funds for her family, which has already gained $4,619 in donations.

An Australian couple abandoned a boy born through a surrogacy deal in India, leaving him stateless, according to new evidence. The couple was reportedly aware that the arrangement was illegal in their home state of New South Wales. They traveled to India in late 2012 and sought citizenship for a baby girl but intended to leave her twin brother behind because they couldn't afford him. Consular staff knew about the case and were concerned about the child's welfare. There were fears that the boy may have been sold, and some officials believed money had changed hands, which would constitute child trafficking. The case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case in Thailand.

Kecil, a baby orangutan, had a difficult start to life after being rejected by his natural mother and a surrogate mother. However, he found love and care with his third surrogate mother, Maggie, an experienced orangutan who has already raised one surrogate child. Maggie has been raising Kecil for the past 10 months, and the two have a strong bond.

Kecil was initially moved from Toledo Zoo to Milwaukee County Zoo after his natural mother failed to bond with him. When he was given to a second surrogate, she also did not form a bond with him. As a last attempt, Kecil was introduced to Maggie, who had already raised four children of her own and another surrogate. Maggie and Kecil immediately showed intimacy, but zookeepers were still nervous Maggie would not take on full parental duties.

A turning point came when a fire alarm sounded at the zoo, scaring Kecil. Instead of turning to people for comfort, he ran to Maggie and cuddled up to her. Maggie has been teaching Kecil how to be an orangutan. Kecil and Maggie will eventually join the zoo's other orangutans in an exhibit but are currently living in isolation, similar to their natural habitat.

Kecil will be on display at Brookfield Zoo's Tropic World Asia enclosure on Saturday and Sunday between 10 am and 12 pm. The other orangutans will be allowed into the enclosure around those times to help them acclimatize. Keepers report that Kecil is adjusting well to his new environment and loves spending time with Maggie.

Paris Saint-Germain star Javier Pastore has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet, asserting that Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Cantona, the former Manchester United forward, had praised Pastore earlier this month, calling him "the best player in the world". However, Pastore, who scored a brace in PSG's 3-1 win at Nice on Saturday, said he doesn't compare himself with the best and that Messi and Ronaldo are incredible players. PSG face Barcelona in the second leg of their last-eight Champions League tie on Tuesday, needing to overhaul a 3-1 deficit to progress to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife from Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust, has been campaigning for over a decade to give mothers more time with their newborns before the umbilical cord is cut. Traditionally, doctors and midwives have clamped the cord within seconds of delivery, but Burleigh believed this was unnatural and potentially harmful. She and her allies, including Dr. David Hutchon, gathered evidence suggesting that immediate cord-clamping could be harmful, particularly for premature babies.

Their efforts have finally convinced the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to change its guidelines. NICE now recommends that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby, and the cord should be clamped within five minutes if possible. This change benefits both the baby's health and allows mothers to hold their babies for a moment while still connected.

However, there has been resistance to the change from some doctors and midwives, who questioned Burleigh's questioning of medical protocol. Despite the pushback, Burleigh felt a moral duty to challenge a practice not grounded in evidence. Dr. Hutchon also notes that hospitals have been blindly clamping and cutting the cord within seconds of birth for decades, without realizing the potential harm.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers are found guilty of sexually assaulting starving children in the Central African Republic. Fourteen soldiers have been accused of abusing children as young as nine in exchange for food. The French defense ministry has denied covering up the scandal, stating that it immediately launched an investigation when it received the news. A UN employee who leaked a report on the allegations has been suspended. If proven true, the allegations are seen as horrible and unacceptable, as French soldiers cannot behave like this in a country where they came to help civilians.

A shocking "resurrection ceremony" for a two-year-old dead boy was captured on camera at a Texas church. The child, identified as Benjamin, was held by Texas pastor's wife Aracely Meza, while others, including her husband Pastor Daniel Meza, were present. The ceremony, which involved the use of oils and prayers, was an attempt to bring the boy back to life. Aracely Meza has been arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission. The church, which also operated as a home, was not registered or zoned to operate as a church. Neighbors reported seeing cars filling the street for services, but the home appeared to be a normal residential property when services were not taking place. An investigation is underway involving both state and federal authorities.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, both from Scotland, had a successful day at the Betfred World Championship on Sunday. Higgins, a four-time champion, defeated Robert Milkins 10-5, showcasing impressive form that had been absent in recent years. Dott, an unseeded player but a previous champion, beat Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins, who had recently doubts about his ability to win again, credited his Welsh Open triumph in February for giving him a boost. He now believes he has a chance to win the title again, which would put him level with Ronnie O'Sullivan. Dott's victory over Walden was a hard-fought battle, but the Scot managed to come out on top. Both Higgins and Dott will continue to represent Scottish snooker in the tournament, with Higgins aiming for a fifth world title and Dott seeking to defend his 2006 title.

Barcelona stars Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano celebrated their important victory over Celta Vigo in La Liga with a matching denim look that was met with some skepticism. The Brazilians played key roles in the win, which saw Barcelona return to the top of the league. Game winner Jeremy Mathieu acknowledged his team's poor performance, attributing it to the international break, but praised the defensive efforts of Gerard Pique.

Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho is planning to sign Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke this summer, with the club's technical director Michael Emenalo having traveled to Spain to watch him play. Mourinho might use Filipe Luis, Chelsea's second-choice left-back, as a makeweight in the deal. Koke, an Atletico academy graduate, has a release clause of around £50 million, which Chelsea might be willing to pay. Koke has been a key player for Atletico, helping them reach the Champions League final last season.

Tom Ballard, a highly accomplished climber, plans to climb K2, 20 years after his mother Alison Hargreaves died descending from the peak. He was six years old at the time, and now sees it as his destiny to follow in her footsteps. Last month, Ballard became the first to solo climb all six of the great north faces of the Alps in the winter season. K2 is considered more difficult to reach than Mount Everest, with dozens dying during attempts to reach the top. Ballard's mother was a revered figure in the climbing world and was only the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. She faced criticism for taking on dangerous climbs while raising a young family, but she shrugged it off, saying fathers who went climbing did not face the same scrutiny. Ballard has clear memories of climbing as a child and always knew it was his calling.

A potential oil reserve of up to 100 billion barrels, worth over $3.7 trillion, has been discovered in the Weald Basin in southern England. The area, which lies under the Home Counties, is estimated to hold as much oil as the entire North Sea. The oil reserves were found at Horse Hill near Gatwick Airport by UKOG (UK Oil & Gas Investments) and its partners. While the consortium believes oil extraction is feasible, industry experts remain skeptical, citing the overly optimistic claims. Stephen Sanderson, UKOG's CEO, believes the site is "world-class" and could significantly contribute to the UK's oil demand within 15 years. However, experts warn that only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction and suggest that fracking might be required for large-scale production. The ownership of the land beneath homes in the area could complicate matters, as the government, not residents, owns the mineral rights.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls, concluding that controlled shooting is not effective and humane. They continue to support cage-trapping and shooting, which they believe should be used to complete the two four-year pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. Animal welfare campaigners criticized the BVA's ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting as regrettable. The Environment Secretary, Liz Truss, promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election. The culls have been criticized by wildlife groups, but the BVA believes they can help reduce bovine TB in cattle.

Modern technology, while meant to make lives easier, often creates more pitfalls in relationships. Social media and smartphones can cause issues on dates, such as constant phone checking, photographing food, and immediately changing relationship statuses on Facebook. To avoid embarrassment, it's important to leave phones off the table, refrain from taking food pictures, and not update relationship statuses after a date. Instead, it's suggested to call a date a few days after the meeting, use Snapchat to update friends, and avoid bragging about Tinder matches. Lastly, it's best to leave Google Glass at home.

Ahead of this weekend's Premier League action, Sportsmail provides team news, provisional squads, betting odds, and Opta stats for Tottenham's home clash with Aston Villa.

Tottenham will be without Kyle Walker, Hugo Lloris, and Jan Vertonghen, while Aston Villa will miss Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, and Carles Gil. Key match stats indicate that Tottenham have won their last five Premier League meetings with Aston Villa, scoring two or more goals in each game. Aston Villa have scored just six goals in their last 12 matches against Tottenham, never more than once in a game. White Hart Lane is the highest scoring stadium in the Premier League this season, while Christian Benteke has scored seven goals in his last five Premier League appearances. Under Tim Sherwood, Benteke has scored at a rate of one goal every 87 minutes in the Premier League.

A mother, Jaye Cox, made the heartbreaking decision to deliver her sick baby, Annabelle, at 20 weeks after scans showed she had a serious form of Spina Bifida. Annabelle was born weighing 290 grams and survived for five minutes. Jaye and her husband, Matthew, contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that turns donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. Angel Gowns created a dress from Jaye's wedding gown for Annabelle to be buried in, allowing her parents and siblings to spend time with her before the funeral. The family now has a replica dress to remember Annabelle by, and they are grateful for the support of Angel Gowns. The organization currently donates outfits to over 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and works directly with families and various children's charities. To donate a wedding dress or volunteer, visit www.angelgownprogram.com.au.

A black police constable named Ronnie Lungu has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police, after the force secretly downgraded his internal assessments to prevent his promotion due to his race. Employment judges found that Wiltshire Police had singled out Mr. Lungu as a "marked man" on grounds of his race. The tribunal concluded that the force's behavior was "so extreme that the Tribunal cannot think of any apparent motive other than one that is directly related to [the] Claimant's race." Despite his treatment, Mr. Lungu remains a PC with the force and hopes to see new procedures put in place to tackle discrimination. Wiltshire Chief Constable Patrick Geenty said the force was "concerned" by the findings and would "learn lessons" from the case.

American YouTube user KentuckyFriedIdiot taught his newborn daughter to suck a plastic water bottle, capturing the moment in a video that has received over 190,000 views. The footage shows the father gnawing on a bottle, then stopping and prompting his child to follow, with the baby obediently mimicking him. The adorable duo then enjoyed bonding time together with their props.

A collection of rare photographs taken by Hugh Owen between 1850 and 1855 offers a glimpse into Bristol's early history. The albumen prints, which will be auctioned off in Cirencester, showcase various locations such as the waterfront, High Street, St Mary Redcliffe church, and St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist. Some sites, like The Fourteen Stars Tavern, have since been demolished or repurposed, while others, like St Mary Redcliffe church, have maintained their appearance over the years. Several areas, like High Street, have undergone significant transformations. These photos provide a snapshot of Bristol before its historic center was devastated by Nazi bombing during World War II.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter, who forced Liam Fox to resign as Defence Secretary, is funding efforts to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate, Tom Tugendhat. Boulter has already donated £30,000 to the Ukip candidate fighting Fox in his Somerset seat and is spending another £30,000 to try to defeat Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. Boulter's vendetta stems from a High Court case in which Sir Michael Tugendhat, Tom's father and a High Court judge, awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages after Boulter made libelous remarks about him on Sky TV. Boulter admits that his actions may seem like revenge, but insists he is merely outraged by what happened in the court case. A Tory Party spokesman declined to comment on the matter.

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood responded to a letter from 6-year-old Charlie Pye, who had applied for the Villa hotseat after Paul Lambert's sacking. Sherwood, who beat Charlie to the job, congratulated the youngster on his credentials and wrote that he was "very close" to being offered the position. Charlie, who is captain of Norton Lindsey, had suggested appointing his parents as assistant managers and provided a range of other requirements, including a chocolate bar as a win bonus and various other perks. Sherwood wished Charlie and Norton Lindsey success in their season and advised him to keep trying, as the club had kept his letter on file "just in case."

Atletico Madrid secured a 2-0 victory over bottom side Cordoba, thanks to a brace from Antoine Griezmann and a goal from Saul Niguez. The win helped Atletico leapfrog Valencia into third place in the La Liga standings, pushing for an automatic Champions League berth. Valencia, currently two points behind Atletico, have a game in hand and can reclaim third place with a win against Villarreal on Sunday. The victory kept Atletico close to Real Madrid, who have 64 points in second place, and leaders Barcelona, who have 68 points.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one, Abby Swinfield, from Castle Donington, Derbyshire, died after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth. She was rushed to the hospital in the early hours of March 30 and placed in a coma, but died a week later from multiple organ failure. Police have arrested a 20-year-old girl on suspicion of supplying Class B drugs, and neighbors claim that ambulances arrived at the property at 1am. After her death, Abby's cousin alleged that her drink was spiked, but police are still waiting for the result of the post-mortem examination. Abby's mother, Kay, is devastated by her daughter's death, and her cousin Lydia Moore described Abby as a perfect girl with an amazing heart. Staffordshire police have arrested a 20-year-old girl on suspicion of supplying drugs and released her on bail. An investigation is ongoing, and a post-mortem examination will take place in the coming days to establish the cause of death.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, raising concerns for the health of children in the area. Soil under a slide at the park in Toshima ward showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit. Authorities believe the radiation could be coming from something buried under the park and have cordoned off the area. The cause of the high radiation levels is still being investigated.

Amir Khan believes Kell Brook is only calling him out for the "one big payday" that has eluded Khan during his career. Brook, who defeated Jo Jo Dan to retain his IBF welterweight title, immediately challenged Khan in a post-fight interview. However, Khan has agreed to a different fight on May 30 and intends to face Brook within the next 12 months. Khan argues that Brook is not a big name in the UK or the US and is only interested in the money their fight would generate. Khan has rejected a fight with Chris Algieri next month, claiming there are better options on the table, and denies his faith is preventing a fight with Brook during Ramadan.

A Dallas architect has designed a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot three-bedroom home using 14 shipping containers. Dubbed 'PV14', the home features a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, a 40ft long swimming pool, and a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. Architects Matt Mooney and Michael Gooden aimed to stay true to the shipping container materials, leaving ceilings exposed and using unpainted containers for bedroom doors. The home's walls are made of sheet rock, and columns were added to restore structural integrity. Spray foam insulation was used to supplement the containers' insulation. A two-story, glass-paneled tower reflects the long, slim pool, and the open-floor first level features polished cement that corresponds to the overhead shipping containers' steel. The upstairs levels have maple wood floors, complementing the views of the nearby park and lake. Deep porches protect the home from direct sunlight while allowing natural light to filter in. Mooney, who had dreamed of building a shipping container home for 25 years, finally found the perfect spot in the same neighborhood where he and his wife, a retired nurse, had lived for 23 years. After more than two years of design and construction, the couple are preparing to move into their unique and sustainable home.

Jordon Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week, following his impressive performances since returning from a loan spell at Derby County. The 19-year-old's contract will keep him at Anfield until 2020. Liverpool also expects to announce Jordan Henderson's new contract and is close to finalizing an extension for Martin Skrtel. Talks are ongoing with young defender Jon Flanagan, whose contract expires in June. Meanwhile, the club has agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.

Comedian Rik Mayall, known for his role as Alan B'Stard in the TV series "The New Statesman," died without a valid will, potentially leaving his family with a large inheritance tax bill. Mayall, who suffered head injuries in a 1998 quad-bike accident and later developed epilepsy, passed away last June at the age of 56. Probate records reveal that he had no will, which could result in complications for his wife of 29 years, Barbara, and their three adult children.

Experts have always advised people to have a valid will to avoid tax pitfalls. Mayall's estate could be liable for tax amounting to tens of thousands of pounds, which would not have been payable if he had left everything to his wife. Under the rules of intestacy, the division of Mayall's net estate of £1,192,701 after funeral and legal expenses is as follows: his wife would receive £250,000 plus all his "chattels" (personal belongings), and their children would automatically inherit a share of the remaining value of the estate, potentially leading to an inheritance tax bill if the amount exceeds the threshold of £325,000.

To avoid the tax, Mayall's family could draft a deed of variation to split up his estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it is below the tax threshold. Mayall's widow declined to discuss the estate and the apparent lack of a will, stating that she had not yet heard from her lawyers.

It was revealed that the writing team behind Alan B'Stard, Laurence Marks and Maurice Gran, also played a significant role in helping David Cameron into No. 10. Though they were supporters of opposite political parties, they were considered local celebrities in their Oxfordshire constituency due to their success with "The New Statesman." They had a hand in recommending Cameron as the Conservative candidate for the Witney seat in 2001, which he went on to win.

The article describes the evacuation of Indian nationals and other foreigners from the war-torn city of Sanaa, Yemen, using Air India planes. Due to the ongoing conflict, these evacuations provide a small window of opportunity for people to leave the city. The evacuees face exhaustion and stress from living in a war zone, and many of them have to leave behind their belongings and lives built over years. The Air India crewmembers work diligently to ensure the safety and comfort of the passengers during these evacuation flights. While many of the evacuees are Indian nationals, others come from various countries and have been working in Yemen. The article highlights the story of a professor who had lived in Yemen for 34 years and had to leave behind his life there due to the ongoing violence. Coordination between various countries, including Saudi Arabia and India, is essential for the success of these evacuation efforts.

An Italian priest has been removed from his position after an online lover provided the church with evidence of the priest engaging in gay orgies, including one with a Swiss Guard. The priest allegedly participated in sex with prostitutes and had explicit gay chats, favoring sexual role-play scenarios involving his lover playing the disciple Judas Iscariot. This scandal is just the latest in a series of sexual controversies within the Vatican.

A new study published in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children with siblings who have autism. The study, which included nearly 95,000 participants, is the latest in a series of research over the past 15 years that has rejected any association between the MMR vaccine and autism.

Previous concerns about the vaccine's role in autism were sparked by a 1998 article by Andrew Wakefield, which has since been retracted and discredited. Despite the overwhelming evidence against a connection, fears persist in some communities. The new study aimed to address these concerns by examining whether vaccines increased autism risk for children with siblings who have autism. The results showed no difference in autism risk between vaccinated and unvaccinated children, regardless of their siblings' diagnoses.

The study also found that children with siblings who have autism are less likely to be vaccinated, with MMR vaccination rates of 92% for children with unaffected siblings compared to 86% for children with affected siblings. An accompanying editorial emphasizes the lack of evidence supporting a connection between MMR vaccine and autism and stresses the importance of vaccinating children to protect public health.

A 12-year-old girl, Jalila, was kidnapped by ISIS fighters from her home in the Yazidi region of Iraq. She was tied up, beaten, and raped by seven different fighters over a period of time. Her story is one of many harrowing accounts of women and children abducted and abused by ISIS.

According to a report by Human Rights Watch, ISIS fighters are kidnapping women and children, forcing them to convert to Islam, and raping them repeatedly. The report states that these actions amount to war crimes, and possibly crimes against humanity. Children as young as eight have been abducted, raped, and forced into marriage.

Jalila escaped her captors, but many others who have managed to escape still feel suicidal due to the traumatic ordeal they experienced. They need better medical and psychological support, which is currently lacking in the community.

Police are searching for Kenneth Stancil, a former student at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, who allegedly shot and killed a college employee, Ron Lane, on Monday morning. The shooting occurred in the campus library, and an active shooter alert was issued. Law enforcement officers from multiple agencies responded to the scene, and a manhunt for Stancil, described as a white male with a goatee and a tattoo over his left eye, is underway. The college was placed on lockdown, and students and staff were evacuated building by building. As of Monday morning, officials confirmed one fatality but did not provide any information about the connection between the suspect and the victim.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council may receive up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to the negative publicity resulting from the grooming scandal. The council is now offering up to £200,000 for the position, higher than the £160,000 earned by former chief boss Martin Kimber. The increase in salary is intended to attract candidates despite the council's reputation following the scandal, which saw 1,400 children suffer horrific sexual abuse over 16 years. However, some opposed the raise, including Councillor Caven Vines, who expressed discomfort with the idea.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during a match against Stoke City. The mask was created by Ortholabsport, an orthopedic center in Milan that has previously made masks for Fernando Torres, Petr Cech, and Demba Ba. Fabregas traveled to Milan with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. The Spanish midfielder could be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday if manager Jose Mourinho selects him. Meanwhile, teammate Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action due to a hamstring problem.

Andros Townsend, an England winger, found motivation in critics like Paul Merson to silence them with a fantastic goal for his country in a friendly match against Italy. The 23-year-old has had an up-and-down season, but England manager Roy Hodgson continued to show faith in him. Townsend delivered, scoring a memorable equalizer in the match, repaying Hodgson's belief in him.

A husband, Joseph O'Riordan, accused of attempting to murder his wife, Amanda, who was having an affair, wrote her a letter from prison asking her to gather his belongings for his trial. He asked for a suit, ties, and other items. Mrs. O'Riordan, who was stabbed eight times by her husband, tearfully testified that the affair was her fault and that she never wanted to hurt him. The trial was adjourned after she broke down in the witness box.

The UK is opening its first three proton beam therapy centers, inspired by the miraculous recovery of five-year-old cancer patient Ashya King, who received the treatment in Prague. The centers, located in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland, are set to open by 2017, with the Cardiff center becoming operational by next year. Proton Partners International, a group formed by UK life sciences and healthcare investors, has committed nearly £100 million in equity finance for this project. The treatment, which targets cancerous cells more precisely than conventional radiotherapy, is currently only available abroad for most patients. However, concerns exist about the long-term impact of the therapy, and it is estimated that only one in 100 people would be suitable for proton beam therapy. The UK government plans to open two NHS proton beam therapy units in 2018.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are recruiting paramedics from Australia due to a shortage of trained staff in Britain. London Ambulance Service held fast-track recruitment events in Sydney, hiring 225 paramedics with £4,500 'golden hello' payments. The selection process was quick, and candidates received an email the next day informing them of their job status. This recruitment strategy is a result of growing numbers of paramedics quitting the NHS due to long wait times at A&E units, frustration with non-urgent calls, and a move to better-paying roles as advanced practitioners. London Ambulance Service is particularly affected, with 340 vacant paramedic posts, 230 of which were quit last year. Australia has a surplus of paramedics, and other understaffed ambulance services in the UK are also recruiting from there and Poland. The first recruitment drive saved the NHS £9 million, and subsequent trips are being considered.

Chelsea are turning to the latest fitness technology, partnering with Technogym, to maintain their lead in the Premier League title race. With a seven-point advantage and a game in hand, Chelsea players like Eden Hazard, Nemanja Matic, and Kurt Zouma are working out at the state-of-the-art Cobham training ground. Technogym's equipment is designed to help elite athletes, and the club believes this partnership will help them achieve even more in the future. The Blues have also signed Juan Cuadrado, who is integrating well into the team. Two Chelsea players, Diego Costa and Eden Hazard, have been nominated for the PFA Player of the Year award, with Hazard being the hot favorite thanks to his consistent performances.

This article discusses the findings of several studies that illustrate the surprising intelligence of babies. In one study, 11-month-old babies were shown to have a strong understanding of physics, as they were able to recognize when objects, like a ball, appeared to defy the laws of gravity. When babies were presented with a ball that seemed to pass through a solid wall or a toy car that floated in the air, they reacted with surprise and tried to understand the phenomenon by banging the ball on a table or dropping the car.

Another study found that infants are capable of understanding complex social situations, such as bullying and friendship, at just 13 months old. These findings suggest that babies have strong feelings about how people should interact and can distinguish between different social situations.

Researchers also discovered that babies are more likely to learn from surprises, as they use these experiences to form new predictions about the world. This innate curiosity helps babies learn more effectively, even at a young age.

Further studies have shown that babies have a remarkable understanding of math and physics, which may be due to some information being so fundamental to survival that we are born with it. Lead author Aimee Stahl noted that young babies are "remarkably sophisticated thinkers" who have rich, complex expectations about the world.

Finally, a separate study found that children who can accurately depict the human form at the age of four are more likely to be brighter in their teenage years. The study showed a link between drawing skills and future intelligence, as the ability to draw is a uniquely human ability that demonstrates cognitive ability.

Manny Pacquiao chose to train outdoors in Los Angeles' Griffith Park on Friday, preparing for his fight with Floyd Mayweather. He ran with fitness enthusiasts and worked on his fitness and stamina. Pacquiao's dog, Pacman, joined him during the run. The boxer shadowboxed and showed off his footwork, demonstrating his confidence in the upcoming bout. Pacquiao recently unveiled his multicolored mouth guard, which comes in a container reading "MouthGuards for Champions." He took a break from the gym to work out on mats, focusing on his core strength with the help of a fitness coach. Pacquiao's colorful mouthpiece for the May 2 Las Vegas fight was also revealed during the training session.

Biso, a cat who had been stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years, has finally been freed. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo, who fed him daily. A social media campaign brought attention to Biso's plight, and animal rights activists successfully rescued the cat after a long and challenging process. Sadly, Biso ran away after being freed, and Uncle Abdo is still searching for him inside the station.

At least 35 workers have been killed in a dairy factory in Yemen after Saudi Arabian warplanes bombed Shiite rebel positions in the country. The airstrikes targeted rebel-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida, hitting warehouses belonging to a factory that produces dairy products. The jets drew return fire from anti-aircraft guns, as the Saudi-led campaign to defeat the Iran-backed Shiite rebels continues its seventh day. The attack on the dairy factory comes as Saudi Arabia hints at preparations for a ground invasion in Yemen in the hope of forcing the Houthi rebels to allow current president, Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi, to return to the country.

Hundreds of commuters in Boston faced delays on April 20, 2023, after a truck crashed on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks. The box truck collided with a car on Interstate 93 southbound in Dorchester, causing both drivers to be hospitalized with non-life-threatening injuries. The crash led to the implementation of replacement shuttle buses for southbound passengers, resulting in long lines. The truck was eventually towed by crane, but traffic remained backed up in both directions. The investigation is ongoing, and no charges have been filed yet.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised his young squad after their European loss to Clermont, but stated that the club will not overspend in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. He mentioned that the club is looking to improve the squad, but they are not interested in signing a high-profile player just for the sake of having a well-known name. McCall believes that the club's young and English-qualified forwards have a bright future ahead of them, and they are willing to wait for the right player to improve the team. The comments come after the club's millionaire chairman Nigel Wray called for the salary cap to be scrapped in order to compete at the highest level in Europe.

The decomposing bodies of the men accused of killing 148 innocent people at a Kenyan university were paraded in front of a large crowd at a primary school today. The authorities drove the naked, bloated corpses of the four alleged terrorists around the town in a pickup truck from the mortuary to Garissa Primary School. This comes as survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, 19, who spent two days hiding in a wardrobe and drinking body lotion to survive, was rescued after al-Shabaab gunmen stormed Garissa University College on Thursday. Paraded: The naked bodies of the alleged attackers were driven around Garissa before the pickup truck parked at a primary school. In the primary school playground, hundreds gathered to look at the bodies of the men accused of being the attackers.

Arsenal must act swiftly to sign Petr Cech this summer or risk losing out on the goalkeeper. Chelsea's Cech is likely to leave Stamford Bridge after losing his starting spot to Thibaut Courtois, and he will discuss his future with manager Jose Mourinho at the end of the season. Arsenal have long admired Cech, but they face competition from other clubs, including Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan. Obstacles for Arsenal include Chelsea's high valuation of Cech and the possibility that the Blues may be reluctant to sell him to a Premier League rival. Cech hopes his long service at Chelsea will allow him to make the final decision on his next club, and he is open to joining Arsenal. Signing Cech would significantly strengthen the Gunners next season, but Chelsea may yet refuse to sell the keeper to their London rivals.

Frankie Dettori will focus on the British Flat season this summer, as Sheik Joaan Al Thani signed up Gregory Benoist to ride Al Shaqab's horses in France. The only exception is Treve, who will continue to be partnered by Thierry Jarnet. Benoist is the only jockey to have ridden Elie Lellouche-trained Ectot, who was unplaced for Al Shaqab in last year’s Arc. Dettori finished third on Al Shaqab’s Moheet in the Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket. Richard Hannon's Kool Kompany won the race, with Hannon hinting that both Craven colts could run in the Guineas. Interestingly, Richard Hughes, who rode Kool Kompany, mentioned that the German or French versions of the Guineas might suit the horse best, run around a bend as opposed to a straight course. Sheik Joaan Al Thani chose not to go with Dettori and insists he's happy with his choice. In other news, AP McCoy's final ride at Cheltenham resulted in an unplaced finish, and he will continue riding at Ayr for the next two days before likely riding again at Sandown’s end-of-season meeting.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," which aired on Nickelodeon in the early 1990s, has died at the age of 78. She died peacefully in Toronto from a rare form of cancer. Lilienstein was one of the most popular children's television performers in North America. The show was known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Lilienstein left the group in 2000.

French free-diving champion Guillaume Néry jumped into Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas, which is the world's second-deepest underwater sinkhole at 660 ft (200 m). As seen in a 2010 video, Néry holds his breath for minutes whiledescending and resurfacing without scuba gear. Though he doesn't reach the bottom, the video is still impressive. Free divers use mind-body control techniques to push their apnoea limits, with some holding their breath for over 20 minutes. The video was filmed by Néry's girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier at Dean's Blue Hole, which is the deepest so-called "blue hole" in the world with an underwater entrance.

A suicide bombing in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, on Saturday, April 18, killed at least 33 people and injured over 100 others. The attack was claimed by ISIS, marking their first claim in Afghanistan. The bomber targeted government workers collecting their pay at the Kabul Bank, according to the terrorist group. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack, condemning it. The United Nations called the violence a possible war crime and highlighted the growing involvement of ISIS in the region, attributing the phenomenon partly to disenfranchised Taliban members seeking media attention.

Laura Wells, an Australian plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched a new eco-friendly swimwear line made entirely from 100% recycled materials. Collaborating with US brand Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy, the collection is inspired by the ocean and features coral reef scenes. The line includes one and two-piece suits in various shapes and sizes, catering to curvy girls. Laura hopes to make a difference by providing environmentally-friendly and fashionable swimsuits for all body types.

The TrackYourDose app, developed by Germany-based esooka, records personal radiation exposure, including exposure from medical exams, changes in location, and flights. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists to calculate radiation levels. It is available for £1.49 ($1.99) on iOS and can measure various types of radiation, including neutron radiation produced in the atmosphere.

The app takes into account cosmic radiation from air travel, gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground, and medical examinations with ionizing radiation such as X-rays or CT scans. Measured in microsieverts (µSv), the annual radiation exposure of a typical person in Europe is around 2,100 µSv.

A ten-hour flight across the North Atlantic can result in a radiation exposure of between 50 µSv to 100 µSv, while an X-ray at a dentist exposes patients to 6 µSv. Blue Bell Ice Cream announced on Friday that it has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility linked to a foodborne illness that caused the deaths of three people. The company is conducting an investigation to determine the exact cause of the contamination. Ten recalled products earlier in March were from a production line at the company's headquarters in Brenham, Texas. The now-recalled ice cream product, available in bulk to institutional accounts like hospitals in 23 states, is not sold in retail locations. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention advises consumers not to eat any Blue Bell brand products made at the Oklahoma facility and asks retailers and institutions not to sell or serve them. The recall began after five patients at a Wichita, Kansas, hospital became ill with listeriosis while hospitalized between December 2013 and January 2015. Officials determined that at least four of the patients drank milkshakes containing Blue Bell ice cream, with three of them later dying. Listeriosis, a life-threatening infection, is caused by eating food contaminated with Listeria monocytogenes bacteria. The disease primarily affects pregnant women, newborns, older adults, and people with weakened immune systems. The CDC identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from the ice cream product traced to the Oklahoma plant. Four of these patients were hospitalized in Texas for unrelated issues before developing listeriosis, with one patient reportedly eating ice cream in a Texas hospital before becoming ill. Blue Bell will conduct a thorough examination of its Oklahoma plant to identify the cause of contamination and ensure improvements are made before resuming operations. The company's other plants in Brenham and Sylacauga, Alabama, continue to operate and supply products to retail stores and institutional customers. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has been notified of the company's decision to voluntarily shut down the plant.

Jon Hamm, star of Mad Men, has been facing the exposure of a college bullying shame involving a hazing incident during his time at the University of Texas at Austin. Court documents revealed that Hamm allegedly set fire to a pledge and used a claw hammer to drag him by his genitals during a hazing ritual gone wrong in 1990. The documents claim that Hamm was charged with assault but managed to get the charges dismissed before his rise to fame. The incident resulted in the shutdown of the Sigma Nu fraternity, with Hamm reaching a plea deal in 1995. Despite the shocking incident, friends of Hamm insist that it was an isolated event and that he has since become a better person.

The Falkland Islands dispute between the UK and Argentina has escalated, with both sides taking diplomatic and legal actions against each other. UK Chancellor Philip Hammond pledged to protect the Falklands from Argentinian "bullying," after Argentina initiated legal action against British oil companies exploring in the region. This follows provocative statements by Argentine President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner, who vowed that the islands would one day be part of Argentina again. The UK has accused Argentina of illegally occupying the islands, while Argentina claims they are part of its territory. The dispute has intensified recently as the UK announced plans to invest £180 million in the Falklands' defenses over the next decade, and Argentina has threatened to prosecute British oil firms working in the area without permission. The UK has rejected Argentina's claims and has criticized the threat of prosecution as unjust and illegitimate.

Passengers experienced an anxious moment when their Delta Air Lines flight landed at LaGuardia Airport in New York City and was met by firefighters in full protective suits. This was due to a reported odor of smoke by the crew moments after the plane touched down. Emergency workers surrounded the aircraft, and firefighters used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source while passengers were still on board. Although there was an odor of electrical wires burning, no smoke was seen. The Delta crew kept passengers informed throughout the situation, and everyone remained calm. The passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes before they were allowed to deplane. The flight was taken out of service for inspection and any necessary maintenance.

David Luiz, the injured Paris Saint-Germain defender, has taken a phrase "twiddling my hair" literally, as shown in his latest Instagram post. He has shared a picture sporting a new hairdo in the style of a man bun. Luiz tore his hamstring during a Ligue 1 match against Marseille and will be out for at least four weeks, missing key matches for his club, including the Champions League quarter-finals against Barcelona. His teammate Lucas Moura finds the new hairdo amusing and shared a picture with Luiz on Instagram, allowing his followers to choose a nickname for the defender's new look. While Luiz's hair might be a joke to his teammates, his injury is a serious concern for manager Laurent Blanc and the club's quest for Ligue 1 and Champions League titles this season.

US President Barack Obama emphasized the importance of diplomacy in addressing Iran's nuclear program, stating that it is the best option for resolving the issue. He made these remarks after the conclusion of a framework agreement with Tehran, which would curb Iran's nuclear program in exchange for lifting economic sanctions. Obama believes that a comprehensive, long-term deal is the best option and plans to keep Congress informed about the details. Critics, including Republicans in the US and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, have expressed concerns about the potential deal, claiming that it could threaten Israel's survival and leave room for Iran to cheat. However, Obama remains confident in the agreement, which still needs to be finalized by June 30.

A 12-year-old girl battling Leukemia for two years has been dismissed from her private Catholic school, St. Joseph's Middle School, due to poor attendance and low academic performance. The school claims to have made several accommodations for the girl, but none were successful in helping her attend school or recover from her illness. The girl's parents argue that the accommodations were insufficient and that she should not be penalized for her poor health. The family has filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights, and the girl's future schooling remains uncertain.

Passive smoking affects plants too, as they can take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. Researchers investigated how nicotine ends up in food crops and plant-derived products, even though it's not allowed in insecticides. They found that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soils and smoke. These findings suggest that nicotine levels in plants may come from sources other than illegal insecticides. The study sheds light on the horizontal transfer of natural products, which could explain the success of farming practices like crop rotation and co-cultivation.

Two chameleons engaged in a fierce battle over a female mate, displaying their color-changing abilities and ambitions. The brief contest took place near the Amber Mountain National Park in Madagascar, where the reptiles were filmed sizing each other up and then snapping at each other. One chameleon proved to be more aggressive and chased his rival out of the tree and along a concrete wall. During their clash, the aggressor took a huge bite out of the other chameleon, who squirmed in pain. The video maker, speaking French, declared it "bataille du chameleons" or battle of the chameleons. The video ends with the defeated chameleon struggling to escape, crawling across a concrete wall as the other chameleon slowly gives chase, before both disappear into the leaves of a tree branch.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove, a 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop, has agreed to join Edinburgh next season on a two-year deal. He has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side, and is looking forward to playing alongside some of his Scotland under 20 teammates at Edinburgh. Cosgrove hopes to strengthen the squad with his set-piece game and learn from players like Alasdair Dickinson. His signing comes as Edinburgh is celebrating their European Cup final appearance, with Andries Strauss and Neil Cochrane applauding the crowd after their semi-final win against Newport Gwent Dragons, and Stuart McInally scoring a try during the same match.

Aaron Hernandez, the former NFL player convicted of murdering Odin Lloyd, has been assigned the prison number W106228 and is being held in Cedar Junction state prison in Massachusetts. He has been moved to the maximum security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center and is currently on suicide watch. He smoked the hallucination-inducing drug in marijuana cigarettes and was reportedly using it for at least a year before the murder of Lloyd.

Hernandez displayed aggressive and unpleasant behavior while under the influence of the drug and was known to regularly smoke marijuana and drink alcohol. Before his arrest, he lived in a $1.3 million mansion and was a heavy drinker who often picked up large bar tabs. He was also seen dancing at a gas station on the night of the murder after smoking marijuana.

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has stated that the club's young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad. As a result, players like Jason Denayer, who has impressed while on loan at Celtic, may be recalled to fill the gap. Celtic are eager to retain Denayer's services, but face an uphill battle due to Premier League regulations requiring clubs to carry a minimum of eight homegrown players. Pellegrini's comments suggest City will be investing heavily in homegrown talent this summer, making players like Denayer, who falls into the homegrown category despite being from Belgium, all the more attractive to the club.

Ander Herrera, the Manchester United midfielder, wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons, as he believes it has brought him good fortune since his time at Athletic Bilbao. He explains that he wants to continue the form that led to his move to the English giants. Herrera had a successful spell at Bilbao, reaching the Copa del Rey and the Europa League finals in his debut season in 2011-12. With a stop-start beginning at Old Trafford, Herrera has recently found his footing in the team and has impressed with a series of strong performances. His seven goals this season, including a double against Aston Villa, have coincided with the club's upturn in results. Herrera revealed that he is a emotional player and hopes to show more emotion as United target silverware in the future.

Despite a crushing 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-finals, Porto supporters gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. Both players and coaches were surprised by the positive reception, with fans congratulating them on their Champions League run. Porto had not reached the quarter-finals since the 2008-09 season, and although they lost to the strong Bayern Munich team, they were proud of their performance in the tournament.

The BBC has developed an online game called "Syrian Journey" which simulates the experience of Syrian refugees trying to flee their war-torn country. Critics argue that the game, which often ends with refugees drowning or being sold to militia, inappropriately turns the suffering of millions into a children's game. Some Twitter users have reacted furiously to the game, which appeared on the BBC site last Wednesday, with one calling it "sickening" and another labeling it "bad taste." The game, which cost up to £20,000 to develop, has received over a million online hits a week, according to a BBC spokesman.

Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokar Tsarnaev has been given another chance by victims Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who have appealed for a life sentence instead of the death penalty. The couple, who lost their legs in the blast, released an emotional statement urging others to "overcome the impulse for vengeance." They also argue that a life sentence without parole would help them and other victims move on faster. The family of eight-year-old bombing victim Martin Richard has made a similar appeal, calling for Tsarnaev to be sentenced to life in prison to "disappear from our collective consciousness as soon as possible." The Richards wrote an op-ed in the Boston Globe, stating that they oppose the death penalty and hope that Tsarnaev's sentencing will not lead to more pain and reliving of the tragedy.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Dr. Ayse Giray, who claimed a 53% stake in the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement came before a ruling on whether Giray could retroactively be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, Euphrates. Although the divorce did not involve the company, Giray based her claim on handwritten notes that she believed confirmed financial support. Chobani settled the suit rather than risk losing $1 billion in assets. Despite this resolution, Chobani still faces challenges, as the company has been considering replacing Ulukaya as CEO since early 2021 due to a 2013 product recall that led to negative EBITDA and other issues.

Diego Costa is targeting Chelsea's crucial clash against Arsenal for his return from a hamstring injury that has sidelined him since the Hull City match. He is expected to miss the games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United but could be ready for the April 26 showdown against Arsenal. Chelsea might consider giving Costa an extended break between now and the end of the season to help him recover fully. Manager Jose Mourinho will not risk Costa's health, and the striker's participation against Arsenal will depend on the team's situation in the title race. In the meantime, Loic Remy will likely start in Chelsea's upcoming games.

The England C team, which is facing the axe after 36 years, may be eliminated as part of FA chairman Greg Dyke's spending review. The team, managed by Paul Fairclough, is composed of non-league players under 23, and has had friendly matches in countries like Bermuda and Jordan. However, the team did not qualify for the semi-finals of the International Challenge Trophy, and fears about its long-term future have increased. If the England C team is axed, it could be due to Greg Dyke's efforts to save money for grassroots football reforms, which include funding for 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. Notable players who have played for England C include George Boyd, Craig Mackail-Smith, and Steve Morison, who went on to play for senior international teams, and Steve Guppy, who won one cap at each level of international football.

James Haskell, the London Wasps captain, showed his excitement for the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie by dressing up as Iron Man and posting a photo on Instagram. The highly-anticipated movie premiered at Westfield London shopping centre with A-list cast members such as Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell, an England flanker, dressed as Iron Man and posted the photo along with a message about transforming himself. Since returning to Wasps in 2012 after playing for various teams in France, Japan, and New Zealand, Haskell has surpassed the 100 appearances mark for the club and become a key member of the England squad.

Police are urging witnesses to come forward after a middle-aged woman launched into a racially-charged tirade against a Muslim woman on a Sydney train. Stacey Eden, 23, stood up for the Muslim woman and her partner, recording the incident and confronting the ranter. The video shows the woman making derogatory comments about Islam, calling the Muslim woman's hijab "stupid," and insulting her husband. Eden defended the couple, telling the woman that her behavior was unacceptable and that she should respect others. The Muslim couple told Eden they were "very grateful" for her stand against the abuse. Police have not yet received any reports of the incident but are encouraging witnesses to come forward.

The mother of Odin Lloyd, Ursula Ward, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Aaron Hernandez, the man convicted of killing her son. Ward's lawyer, Douglas Sheff, said Hernandez will be called to testify during the trial, and Ward wants to look him in the eye when he does. Hernandez was convicted of first-degree murder on April 15 for the June 17, 2013 shooting death of Lloyd. Ward believes Hernandez shot her son out of jealousy, as Lloyd had been dating the sister of Hernandez's fiancée.

The civil lawsuit, filed in December 2013, was put on hold during the criminal trial but is now set to resume. The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, and although Hernandez's team, the New England Patriots, was initially named in the suit, they have been dismissed from the case after agreeing to release any money

Britain has discovered oil in the Falkland Islands, a move that could escalate tensions with Argentina, which also lays claim to the territory. The discovery, announced by British companies Premier Oil, Rockhopper Exploration, and Falkland Oil & Gas, is estimated to hold 100 million barrels of oil and was made at the Zebedee exploratory well, located about 130 miles north of the main island. This find comes amid heightened tensions on the 33rd anniversary of the Falklands conflict, with Argentine officials threatening to prosecute oil companies operating in the area, claiming they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. The new discovery could lead to further claims by Argentina, with some predicting increased tensions between the two countries.

A CCTV video captured a brutal attack on a three-legged cat named Freeman by two dogs in Tarring, West Sussex. The attack left the disabled cat dead in the neighbor's garden. The video shows a woman in a blue car arriving at the scene, apparently calling the dogs over, and then leaving without intervening. Police are investigating the incident and are searching for the owner of the dogs, which are believed to be Dobermans. Neighbors are distraught by the horrific attack and the callousness of the dog owners, who did not check on the cat after the incident.

A Chinese woman, Zhu Diandian, has become an internet sensation after sharing her close relationship with her pet pig, Five Flowers. The woman has raised Five Flowers since it was a piglet, and they now share a bed together every day. Zhu Diandian's husband is reportedly tolerant of the relationship, but their pet dog seems to be envious of the pig. Zhu Diandian's nickname for her pet, "crazy pig," has led to her becoming an internet sensation in China, with legions of netizens commenting on her unusual pet. The owner's surname, Zhu, sounds like "pig" in Mandarin, which may be the reason for her love of the animal. The woman works at a publishing company in Beijing and has almost 40,000 followers on Weibo. She lives with her husband, Five Flowers, a pet dog, and a rabbit, and takes her pig for walks with a green T-shirt and a body harness. Zhu Diandian even takes steps to ensure Five Flowers is well taken care of, like leading the pig to the bathroom with a trail of green vegetables for a bath.
